ps.bmp\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></a>Tis the season for giving and what better way than to give a dog, cat, puppy or kitten a new home?  We have some fantastic animals just waiting for a chance to meet someone like you.  Whether you\'re looking for a playful puppy or kitten, a running buddy or an older lady or gentleman you\'ll find your perfect match here at the Animal Defense League!\r\n\r\nWe\'re helping make it even easier this weekend by joining the city-wide \"Whiskers in Wonderland\" Adoption event.  On December 8 and 9, all dogs AND puppies will be just $40!  Cats and kittens are only $15!\r\n\r\nIf you cannot make it this weekend, no worries! Every other day in the month of December is our \"Take Me Home for the Holidays\" special.  Puppies are $60, dogs are $40 and cats and kittens are $15 all month long.\r\n\r\nAs always, our animals are already spayed/neutered, vaccinated and micro-chipped.  All they need is a place to call home and that\'s where YOU come in to play.\r\n\r\nAlthough we do not encourage giving pets as gifts, adding one to the family with everyone being involved in the adoption process is a perfect present.  As always, you can check out some of our fantastic animals at <a href=\"http://www.adltexas.org\">www.adltexas.org</a>.','Home for the Holidays','','publish','open','open','','home-for-the-holidays','','','2013-12-06 15:03:36','2013-12-06 21:03:36','',0,'http://blog.adltexas.org/?p=201',0,'post','',0),(202,2,'2013-12-06 14:59:38','2013-12-06 20:59:38','','mistletoe','','inherit','open','open','','mistletoe','','','2013-12-06 14:59:38','2013-12-06 20:59:38','',201,'http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/mistletoe.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(203,2,'2013-12-06 15:01:24','2013-12-06 21:01:24','','pups','','inherit','open','open','','pups','','','2013-12-06 15:01:24','2013-12-06 21:01:24','',201,'http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/pups.bmp',0,'attachment','image/bmp',0),(204,2,'2013-12-06 15:01:42','2013-12-06 21:01:42','<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/mistletoe.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-202 alignleft\" alt=\"mistletoe\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/mistletoe-150x150.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a><a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/pups.bmp\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-203\" alt=\"pups\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/pups.bmp\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></a>Tis the season for giving and what better way than to give a dog, cat, puppy or kitten a new home?  We have some fantastic animals just waiting for a chance to meet someone like you.  Whether you\'re looking for a playful puppy or kitten, a running buddy or an older lady or gentleman you\'ll find your perfect match here at the Animal Defense League!\r\n\r\nWe\'re helping make it even easier this weekend by joining the city-wide \"Whiskers in Wonderland\" Adoption event.  On December 8 and 9, all dogs AND puppies will be just $40!  Cats and kittens are only $15!\r\n\r\nIf you cannot make it this weekend, no worries! Every other day in the month of December is our \"Take Me Home for the Holidays\" special.  Puppies are $60, dogs are $40 and cats and kittens are $15 all month long.\r\n\r\nAs always, our animals are already spayed/neutered, vaccinated and micro-chipped.  All they need is a place to call home and that\'s where YOU come in to play.\r\n\r\nAlthough we do not encourage giving pets as gifts, adding one to the family with everyone being involved in the adoption process is a perfect present.  As always, you can check out some of our fantastic animals at <a href=\"http://www.adltexas.org\">www.adltexas.org</a>.','Home for the Holidays','','inherit','open','open','','201-revision-v1','','','2013-12-06 15:01:42','2013-12-06 21:01:42','',201,'http://blog.adltexas.org/uncategorized/201-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(205,2,'2013-12-06 15:03:02','2013-12-06 21:03:02','','gift','','inherit','open','open','','gift','','','2013-12-06 15:03:02','2013-12-06 21:03:02','',201,'http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/gift.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(209,2,'2013-12-31 13:50:40','2013-12-31 19:50:40','<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/nye.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-210\" alt=\"nye\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/nye-150x150.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Believe it or not, it\'s almost time to ring out 2013 and ring in 2014.  In just a few short hours it\'ll be a new year!  You can bet there will be plenty of parties and lots of noisemakers when the clock strikes midnight.  So let\'s not take the term\"party animals\" literally.  You need to be especially protective of your dog and cat tonight.  New Year\'s Eve is a time of year when lots of pets get scared of all the noise and fireworks and bolt.  Here are few tips to make sure your best friend stays home tonight:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Make sure your pet is wearing a collar with identification tags.  The pet\'s name and a current phone number are ideal.  If your pet is microchipped, please take a few minutes to make sure your information with the microchip company is current.  We see dogs and cats come in all of the time with microchips, but with old information making it next to impossible to find their owners.</li>\r\n	<li>Keep your pet indoors in a quiet area.  You want them to feel safe and sound.  Make sure your buddy has plenty of fresh water and give dogs a few chew toys (mine LOVE their peanut butter-filled Kong toys, especially if I freeze them).  Dogs who are crate trained may feel safest in their kennels.  Cats will do best in a bathroom or utility room with food, water and their litter box.</li>\r\n	<li>If left outdoors, frightened dogs often jump high fences and dig holes to escape the sound of fireworks. Indoor animals should be kept away from glass windows or doors.  Some are capable of crashing right through glass if they get scared.</li>\r\n	<li>If you\'re hosting a party, keep your pet in a separate room.  Even friendly dogs and cats can get overwhelmed.</li>\r\n	<li>As always, make sure to keep all alcohol, festive foods/chocolates, floral arrangements and party decorations away from your pets.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA New Year is definitely something to be celebrated, but your pet doesn\'t need to be a part of the part.  Be safe and HAPPY NEW YEAR!','Happy New Year!','','publish','open','open','','happy-new-year','','','2013-12-31 13:50:40','2013-12-31 19:50:40','',0,'http://blog.adltexas.org/?p=209',0,'post','',0),(264,88890,'2014-01-16 12:33:10','2014-01-16 18:33:10','[caption id=\"attachment_235\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/IMG_0042.jpg\"><img src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/IMG_0042-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"January after her recent trip to the &quot;spa&quot;\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-235\" /></a> January after her recent trip to the \"spa\"[/caption]\r\n\r\nJanuary is a 1 year old Terrier mix who was brought to ADL as a stray. She suffers from a skin condition known as mange. The condition attacks the hair follicles and if left untreated, causes severe hair loss and can lead to other skin conditions. With almost her entire coat lost to the mange, she will require regular dips and treatments. I am quite happy to announce that January has found a loving foster home. Moreover, her foster family has previous experience with thses extreme mange cases. Stay tuned for updates regarding January.</p>\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_233\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/IMG_0037.jpg\"><img src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/IMG_0037-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"January and her new Foster family.\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-233\" /></a> January and her new Foster family.[/caption]\r\n\r\nFor more information regarding the Foster Program, please contact 210.655.1481 ext.123 or by email at foster@adltexas.org.','January Found A Foster','','inherit','open','open','','259-revision-v1','','','2014-01-16 12:33:10','2014-01-16 18:33:10','',259,'http://blog.adltexas.org/uncategorized/259-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(212,2,'2013-12-31 13:48:58','2013-12-31 19:48:58','Believe it or not, it\'s almost time to ring out 2013 and ring in 2014.  In just a few short hours it\'ll be a new year!  You can bet there will be plenty of parties and lots of noisemakers when the clock strikes midnight.  Even though \"party animals\" is a fun way to describe some of folks, let\'s not take it literally.  You need to be especially protective of your dog and cat tonight.  New Year\'s Eve is a time of year when lots of pets get scared of all the noise and fireworks and bolt.  Here are few easy tips to make sure your best friend stays home tonight:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Make sure your pet is wearing a collar with identification tags.  The pet\'s name and a current phone number are ideal.  If your pet is microchipped, please take a few minutes to make sure your information with the microchip company is current.  We see dogs and cats come in all of the time with microchips, but with old information making it next to impossible to find their owners.</li>\r\n	<li>Keep your pet indoors in a quiet area.  You want them to feel safe and sound.  Make sure your buddy has plenty of fresh water and give dogs a few chew toys (mine LOVE their peanut butter-filled Kong toys, especially if I freeze them).  Dogs who are crate trained may feel safest in their kennels.  Cats will do best in a bathroom or utility room with food, water and their litter box.</li>\r\n	<li>If left outdoors, frightened dogs often jump high fences and dig holes to escape the sound of fireworks. Indoor animals should be