/?p=236',0,'post','',0),(237,88890,'2014-01-14 08:08:18','2014-01-14 14:08:18','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','open','','236-revision-v1','','','2014-01-14 08:08:18','2014-01-14 14:08:18','',236,'http://blog.adltexas.org/uncategorized/236-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(238,88890,'2014-01-14 08:08:31','2014-01-14 14:08:31','','Auto Draft','','trash','open','open','','auto-draft-3','','','2014-01-14 08:09:07','2014-01-14 14:09:07','',0,'http://blog.adltexas.org/?p=238',0,'post','',0),(239,88890,'2014-01-14 08:08:55','2014-01-14 14:08:55','','chi2013','','inherit','open','open','','chi2013','','','2014-01-14 08:08:55','2014-01-14 14:08:55','',238,'http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/chi2013.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(240,88890,'2014-01-14 08:09:07','2014-01-14 14:09:07','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','open','','238-revision-v1','','','2014-01-14 08:09:07','2014-01-14 14:09:07','',238,'http://blog.adltexas.org/uncategorized/238-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(268,2,'2014-01-24 11:06:02','2014-01-24 17:06:02','[caption id=\"attachment_275\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"150\"]<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Buffy-3.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-275  \" alt=\"\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Buffy-3-150x150.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a> Buffy still loves to play![/caption]\r\n\r\nSenior dogs can be the real heartbreakers for shelters.  It’s tough to see older dogs lose their homes.  In many cases, they have had the same owner for years and they have no idea what is going on in their world.  Sometimes they’re scared, nervous, upset … all of the things we would feel if we were being forced from our homes.  It’s also hard to see these wonderful dogs get passed over for the younger ones.  Even a dog that’s only 5-years-old can be considered “too old” by some people.  Logically we all know that these dogs still have many years and so much to offer, but all too often they are passed over simply because of their age.\r\n\r\nBefore you walk past the more mature dogs, really think about what you’re missing.   The best part is that they’re past the puppy stage!  They are likely housebroken, trained and not as likely to chew on your favorite pair of shoes.  Don’t get me wrong, I love puppies, but older dogs already have so much personality.  It’s like meeting a new friend who already brings so much to the relationship.  I don’t have to teach them, we just have to learn from each other.  Now that’s the start of a beautiful friendship!\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_271\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/snoopy.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-271  \" alt=\"snoopy\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/snoopy-150x150.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a> Snoopy can still run with the younger dogs![/caption]\r\n\r\nI had the pleasure of taking a few of our older furry friends out for walks this past weekend and they were such a pleasure.  They were just as active as the younger dogs, but not as likely to yank my arm out of socket.  They already knew that walking with me was going to get them the most treats, chances to smell and definitely the most attention.  Quite frankly, they knew the game and they played it very well.\r\n\r\nMany shelters will offer discounts or specials for senior dogs, not because they aren’t worth as much as the younger ones.  On the contrary, we KNOW they are special.  Shelters do this because all of them deserve to live out their golden years with dignity and love, just like we do.  So if you’re looking to adopt a dog give a senior dog a second chance.\r\n\r\n<em>Check out our \"Oldies but Goodies\" at the Animal Defense League of Texas by clicking <a title=\"Oldies but Goodies\" href=\"http://adltexas.org/category/pets/oldies-but-goodies/\">here</a>.</em>','Senior Dogs are Special!','','publish','open','open','','senior-dogs-are-special','','','2014-01-24 11:06:02','2014-01-24 17:06:02','',0,'http://blog.adltexas.org/?p=268',0,'post','',0),(293,88890,'2014-02-01 10:09:19','2014-02-01 16:09:19','[caption id=\"attachment_294\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/William_Harry_Diana.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-294\" alt=\"Little William, Harry &amp; Diana are all set for their new foster home.\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/William_Harry_Diana-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Little William, Harry &amp; Diana are all set for their new foster home.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThis adorable trio of Maltipoos have found a fantastic foster home and will be ready for adoption very soon.\r\n\r\nFor more information regarding the ADL Foster Program, please contact foster@adltexas.org or 210-655-1481 ext.123','Update - William, Harry & Diana','','publish','open','open','','update-william-harry-diana','','','2014-02-01 10:09:46','2014-02-01 16:09:46','',0,'http://blog.adltexas.org/?p=293',0,'post','',0),(244,88889,'2014-01-14 11:32:31','2014-01-14 17:32:31','<p><a href=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/chi_fosters.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-225\" alt=\"chi_fosters\" src=\"http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/chi_fosters-300x290.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"290\" /></a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>These fun little Chihuahua mixes were originally brought in at just 5 days old. They are just about ready for adoption, but could use about 2 more weeks of TLC with a loving foster.</p>\n<p>Interested in fostering? Contact 210-655-1481 ext.123 or foster@adltexas.org</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n','Available Fosters','','inherit','open','open','','224-autosave-v1','','','2014-01-14 11:32:31','2014-01-14 17:32:31','',224,'http://blog.adltexas.org/uncategorized/224-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(245,88890,'2014-01-14 12:03:08','2014-