> Maxwell waiting for his x-ray[/caption]\n\nJudging by the photo above of Maxwell, you would never know he had suffered a major injury to his leg during a hit and run accident. This photo was literally taken minutes after Maxwell was brought into ADL. Maxwell has since had his','Maxwell & Kilowatt','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-01-16 13:04:53','2014-01-16 19:04:53','',0,'http://blog.adltexas.org/?p=265',0,'post','',0),(266,88890,'2014-01-16 12:46:11','2014-01-16 18:46:11','','maxwell1','Maxwell waiting for his x-ray','inherit','open','open','','maxwell1','','','2014-01-16 12:46:11','2014-01-16 18:46:11','',265,'http://blog.adltexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/maxwell1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(269,2,'2014-01-24 10:50:41','2014-01-24 16:50:41','Senior dogs can be the real heartbreakers for shelters.  It’s tough to see older dogs lose their homes.\r\n\r\nIn many cases, they have had the same owner for years and they have no idea what is going on in their world.  Sometimes they’re scared, nervous, upset … all of the things we would feel if we were being forced from our homes.  It’s also hard to see these wonderful dogs get passed over for the younger ones.  Even a dog that’s only 5-years-old can be considered “too old” by some people.\r\n\r\nBefore you walk past the more mature dogs, really think about what you’re missing.   The best part is that they’re past the puppy stage!  They are likely housebroken, trained and not as likely to chew on your favorite pair of shoes.  Don’t get me wrong, I love puppies, but older dogs already have so much personality.  It’s like meeting a new friend who already brings so much to the relationship.  I don’t have to teach them, we just have to learn from each other.  Now that’s the start of a beautiful friendship!\r\n\r\nI had the pleasure of taking a few of our older furry friends out for walks this past weekend and they were such a pleasure.  They were just as active as the younger dogs, but not as likely 